# OWASP Top 10 for Node.js Developers

## Why Security Matters for Backend Developers

Every backend application is a target. Whether you are building a startup MVP or a large-scale enterprise system, attackers will probe your API endpoints, attempt to steal user data, and exploit overlooked vulnerabilities. The Open Web Application Security Project (OWASP) maintains a regularly updated list of the ten most critical web application security risks. Understanding these risks is not optional -- it is a fundamental part of writing production-grade backend code.

This lesson walks through the OWASP Top 10 (2021 edition) from the perspective of a Node.js developer, with concrete code examples showing both vulnerable and secure patterns.

## The OWASP Top 10 at a Glance

```
+------+------------------------------------------+------------------+
| Rank | Category                                 | Severity         |
+------+------------------------------------------+------------------+
| A01  | Broken Access Control                    | Critical         |
| A02  | Cryptographic Failures                   | Critical         |
| A03  | Injection                                | High             |
| A04  | Insecure Design                          | High             |
| A05  | Security Misconfiguration                | High             |
| A06  | Vulnerable and Outdated Components       | Medium-High      |
| A07  | Identification and Authentication Fail.  | High             |
| A08  | Software and Data Integrity Failures     | Medium-High      |
| A09  | Security Logging and Monitoring Failures | Medium           |
| A10  | Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)       | Medium-High      |
+------+------------------------------------------+------------------+
```

## A01: Broken Access Control

Broken access control is the number one vulnerability. It happens when users can act outside their intended permissions -- viewing another user's data, modifying records they should not have access to, or escalating privileges.

### Vulnerable Pattern: Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR)

```js
// VULNERABLE: No authorization check
app.get('/api/users/:id/profile', async (req, res) => {
  const profile = await prisma.user.findUnique({
    where: { id: parseInt(req.params.id) },
  });
  res.json(profile); // Any authenticated user can view ANY profile
});
```

### Secure Pattern: Enforce Ownership

```js
// SECURE: Verify the requesting user owns the resource
app.get('/api/users/:id/profile', authenticate, async (req, res) => {
  const userId = parseInt(req.params.id);

  // Check that the authenticated user is requesting their own data
  // or has admin privileges
  if (req.user.id !== userId && req.user.role !== 'ADMIN') {
    return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Forbidden' });
  }

  const profile = await prisma.user.findUnique({
    where: { id: userId },
  });

  if (!profile) {
    return res.status(404).json({ error: 'User not found' });
  }

  res.json(profile);
});
```

### Key Defenses

- Deny by default. Every route should require authentication unless explicitly public.
- Check resource ownership in every handler, not just at the route level.
- Use middleware to enforce role-based access.
- Avoid exposing sequential IDs -- use UUIDs instead.

```js
// Middleware for role-based access
function requireRole(...roles) {
  return (req, res, next) => {
    if (!roles.includes(req.user.role)) {
      return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Insufficient permissions' });
    }
    next();
  };
}

app.delete('/api/users/:id', authenticate, requireRole('ADMIN'), async (req, res) => {
  // Only admins reach this code
  await prisma.user.delete({ where: { id: req.params.id } });
  res.status(204).end();
});
```

## A02: Cryptographic Failures

Cryptographic failures occur when sensitive data is not properly protected -- in transit, at rest, or during processing.

```
+-------------------------------------------------------------------+
|                    Data Protection Checklist                       |
+-------------------------------------------------------------------+
| In Transit:   HTTPS/TLS everywhere, HSTS headers                  |
| At Rest:      Encrypt database, encrypt backups                   |
| Passwords:    bcrypt/argon2, NEVER plaintext or MD5/SHA            |
| Secrets:      Environment variables, never in code                |
| API Keys:     Rotate regularly, scope permissions                 |
+-------------------------------------------------------------------+
```

```js
// VULNERABLE: Storing passwords with MD5
const crypto = require('node:crypto');
const hash = crypto.createHash('md5').update(password).digest('hex');

// SECURE: Using bcrypt with proper cost factor
const bcrypt = require('bcrypt');
const SALT_ROUNDS = 12;

async function hashPassword(password) {
  return bcrypt.hash(password, SALT_ROUNDS);
}

async function verifyPassword(password, hash) {
  return bcrypt.compare(password, hash);
}
```

```js
// VULNERABLE: Secrets hardcoded in source
const stripe = require('stripe')('sk_live_abc123xyz');

// SECURE: Secrets from environment
const stripe = require('stripe')(process.env.STRIPE_SECRET_KEY);
```

## A03: Injection

Injection attacks occur when untrusted data is sent to an interpreter as part of a command or query. SQL injection is the most well-known variant, but NoSQL injection, OS command injection, and LDAP injection are all risks.

We cover SQL injection in depth in lesson 7.1.2. Here is a quick preview:

```js
// VULNERABLE: String concatenation in SQL
const query = `SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = '${req.body.email}'`;

// SECURE: Parameterized query
const result = await pool.query(
  'SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = $1',
  [req.body.email]
);
```

## A04: Insecure Design

Insecure design refers to fundamental architectural flaws that cannot be fixed by perfect implementation. It is about missing or ineffective control design.

```js
// INSECURE DESIGN: No rate limiting on password reset
app.post('/api/auth/reset-password', async (req, res) => {
  const token = generateResetToken();
  await sendResetEmail(req.body.email, token);
  res.json({ message: 'Reset email sent' });
});

// SECURE DESIGN: Rate limiting + token expiry + account lockout
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const resetLimiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 3,                    // 3 attempts per window
  message: { error: 'Too many reset attempts, try again later' },
});

app.post('/api/auth/reset-password', resetLimiter, async (req, res) => {
  const token = crypto.randomBytes(32).toString('hex');
  const expiry = new Date(Date.now() + 30 * 60 * 1000); // 30 min expiry

  await prisma.passwordReset.create({
    data: {
      email: req.body.email,
      token: await bcrypt.hash(token, 10),
      expiresAt: expiry,
    },
  });

  await sendResetEmail(req.body.email, token);

  // Always return the same response to prevent email enumeration
  res.json({ message: 'If that email exists, a reset link was sent' });
});
```

## A05: Security Misconfiguration

This is the most common vulnerability in real-world applications. Default configurations, open cloud storage, verbose error messages, and missing security headers all fall here.

```js
// Use helmet to set security headers automatically
const helmet = require('helmet');
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.use(helmet());

// helmet sets these headers (and more):
// X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
// X-Frame-Options: DENY
// X-XSS-Protection: 0 (relies on CSP instead)
// Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=15552000; includeSubDomains
// Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'
```

```js
// VULNERABLE: Leaking stack traces to clients
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  res.status(500).json({
    error: err.message,
    stack: err.stack,  // NEVER expose this in production
  });
});

// SECURE: Generic error in production, details in development
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack); // Log the full error server-side

  const isDev = process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development';
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({
    error: isDev ? err.message : 'Internal Server Error',
    ...(isDev && { stack: err.stack }),
  });
});
```

### Security Headers Diagram

```
Browser Request
    |
    v
+-------------------+
|    Your Server    |
+-------------------+
    |
    v  Response Headers:
    +-- Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'
    +-- X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
    +-- X-Frame-Options: DENY
    +-- Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000
    +-- Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin
    +-- Permissions-Policy: camera=(), microphone=()
    |
    v
Browser enforces all these policies
```

## A06: Vulnerable and Outdated Components

Node.js projects pull in hundreds of transitive dependencies. A single vulnerable package in your `node_modules` can compromise your entire application.

```bash
# Check for known vulnerabilities
npm audit

# Fix automatically where possible
npm audit fix

# See detailed report
npm audit --json

# Use Snyk for deeper analysis
npx snyk test
```

```js
// package.json best practices
{
  "scripts": {
    "audit": "npm audit --audit-level=high",
    "preinstall": "npx npm-force-resolutions"
  },
  "overrides": {
    // Force specific version of a transitive dependency
    "minimist": ">=1.2.6"
  }
}
```

Automate dependency updates with tools like Dependabot or Renovate. Run `npm audit` in your CI/CD pipeline and fail the build on high-severity vulnerabilities.

## A07: Identification and Authentication Failures

```js
// VULNERABLE: Weak session configuration
app.use(session({
  secret: 'keyboard cat',          // Weak, predictable secret
  cookie: {},                       // No secure flags
}));

// SECURE: Proper session configuration
app.use(session({
  secret: process.env.SESSION_SECRET, // Strong, random secret
  name: '__Host-sid',                  // Prefixed cookie name
  resave: false,
  saveUninitialized: false,
  cookie: {
    secure: true,                      // HTTPS only
    httpOnly: true,                    // No JavaScript access
    sameSite: 'strict',                // CSRF protection
    maxAge: 1000 * 60 * 60 * 24,      // 24 hours
  },
  store: new RedisStore({ client: redisClient }), // External store
}));
```

## A08: Software and Data Integrity Failures

This covers situations where code or data is modified without integrity verification. Subresource integrity, CI/CD pipeline security, and deserialization attacks fall here.

```js
// VULNERABLE: Deserializing untrusted data
const obj = JSON.parse(untrustedInput);
// If this is used with eval() or Function(), it becomes code execution

// Also vulnerable: using node-serialize or similar packages
// that support function deserialization
const serialize = require('node-serialize');
const obj = serialize.unserialize(userInput); // Remote code execution!

// SECURE: Validate deserialized data with a schema
const { z } = require('zod');

const UserInputSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string().max(100),
  email: z.string().email(),
  age: z.number().int().min(0).max(150),
});

const parsed = UserInputSchema.safeParse(JSON.parse(untrustedInput));
if (!parsed.success) {
  return res.status(400).json({ errors: parsed.error.issues });
}
```

## A09: Security Logging and Monitoring Failures

If you cannot detect an attack, you cannot respond to it. Most breaches go undetected for months.

```js
const winston = require('winston');

const securityLogger = winston.createLogger({
  level: 'info',
  format: winston.format.combine(
    winston.format.timestamp(),
    winston.format.json()
  ),
  defaultMeta: { service: 'auth-service' },
  transports: [
    new winston.transports.File({ filename: 'security.log' }),
  ],
});

// Log security-relevant events
function logSecurityEvent(event, details) {
  securityLogger.warn({
    event,
    ...details,
    timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),
  });
}

// Examples of what to log:
app.post('/api/auth/login', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await findUser(req.body.email);

  if (!user || !(await verifyPassword(req.body.password, user.hash))) {
    logSecurityEvent('LOGIN_FAILED', {
      email: req.body.email,
      ip: req.ip,
      userAgent: req.get('User-Agent'),
    });
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Invalid credentials' });
  }

  logSecurityEvent('LOGIN_SUCCESS', {
    userId: user.id,
    ip: req.ip,
  });

  // ... issue token
});
```

### What to Log

```
+----------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| Always Log                       | Never Log                         |
+----------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
| Login attempts (success + fail)  | Passwords (even hashed)           |
| Authorization failures           | Full credit card numbers          |
| Input validation failures        | Social security numbers           |
| Admin actions                    | Session tokens / JWTs             |
| Data exports / bulk downloads    | API keys or secrets               |
| Account changes (email, role)    | Personal health information       |
+----------------------------------+-----------------------------------+
```

## A10: Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)

SSRF occurs when an application fetches a remote resource based on user-supplied input without proper validation. We cover this in detail in lesson 7.1.3.

```js
// VULNERABLE: Fetching arbitrary URLs
app.post('/api/fetch-metadata', async (req, res) => {
  const response = await fetch(req.body.url);
  const data = await response.json();
  res.json(data);
});
// Attacker can request: http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/
// (AWS metadata endpoint - leaks credentials)

// SECURE: Validate and restrict URLs
const { URL } = require('node:url');
const dns = require('node:dns/promises');
const net = require('node:net');

async function isUrlSafe(inputUrl) {
  const parsed = new URL(inputUrl);

  // Only allow HTTPS
  if (parsed.protocol !== 'https:') return false;

  // Resolve DNS and check for private IPs
  const addresses = await dns.resolve4(parsed.hostname);
  for (const addr of addresses) {
    if (net.isIP(addr) && isPrivateIP(addr)) return false;
  }

  return true;
}

function isPrivateIP(ip) {
  const parts = ip.split('.').map(Number);
  return (
    parts[0] === 10 ||
    parts[0] === 127 ||
    (parts[0] === 172 && parts[1] >= 16 && parts[1] <= 31) ||
    (parts[0] === 192 && parts[1] === 168) ||
    (parts[0] === 169 && parts[1] === 254)
  );
}
```

## Putting It All Together: Security Middleware Stack

```js
const express = require('express');
const helmet = require('helmet');
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
const cors = require('cors');

const app = express();

// 1. Security headers
app.use(helmet());

// 2. CORS - restrict origins
app.use(cors({
  origin: process.env.ALLOWED_ORIGINS?.split(',') || 'https://myapp.com',
  credentials: true,
}));

// 3. Rate limiting
app.use(rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000,
  max: 100,
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
}));

// 4. Body parsing with size limits
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));

// 5. Remove fingerprinting
app.disable('x-powered-by');

// 6. Trust proxy (if behind reverse proxy)
app.set('trust proxy', 1);
```

```
Request Flow Through Security Layers:

Client --> [TLS/HTTPS] --> [Rate Limiter] --> [CORS Check]
   --> [Helmet Headers] --> [Body Parser + Size Limit]
   --> [Authentication] --> [Authorization] --> [Input Validation]
   --> [Route Handler] --> [Response]
```

## Security Audit Checklist

1. Run `npm audit` and resolve all high/critical vulnerabilities
2. Verify all environment secrets are loaded from env vars, not hardcoded
3. Confirm HTTPS is enforced with HSTS headers
4. Test that error responses do not leak stack traces in production
5. Verify rate limiting on authentication endpoints
6. Check that all database queries use parameterized statements
7. Confirm security-relevant events are logged
8. Review CORS configuration to ensure it is not set to `*` in production
9. Verify session cookies use `secure`, `httpOnly`, and `sameSite` flags
10. Check that file uploads are validated for type and size

7.1.2.body:
# SQL Injection: Attack Vectors and Prevention

## What Is SQL Injection?

SQL injection (SQLi) is one of the oldest and most devastating web application vulnerabilities. It occurs when an attacker can insert or manipulate SQL statements through user-controlled input that gets incorporated into database queries. Despite being well-understood for over two decades, SQL injection remains in the OWASP Top 10 and continues to cause real-world breaches.

The core problem is simple: treating user input as code instead of data.

## How SQL Injection Works

```
Normal Login Flow:

User Input:  email = "alice@example.com", password = "secret123"
Built Query: SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = 'alice@example.com' AND password = '...'
Result:      Returns Alice's row (or nothing if password is wrong)


SQL Injection Attack:

User Input:  email = "' OR '1'='1' --", password = "anything"
Built Query: SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = '' OR '1'='1' --' AND password = '...'
                                                   ^^^^^^^^^^  ^^
                                                   Always true  Comment (ignores rest)
Result:      Returns ALL users -- attacker bypasses authentication
```

The `--` is a SQL comment that causes the database to ignore the rest of the query, including the password check.

## Types of SQL Injection

### 1. Classic (In-Band) SQL Injection

The attacker gets results directly in the application response.

```js
// VULNERABLE: String concatenation builds a dynamic query
app.get('/api/users', async (req, res) => {
  const { search } = req.query;
  // If search = "'; DROP TABLE users; --"
  // The query becomes: SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = ''; DROP TABLE users; --'
  const result = await pool.query(
    `SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = '${search}'`
  );
  res.json(result.rows);
});
```

### 2. Blind SQL Injection

The attacker does not see query results directly but infers information based on application behavior.

**Boolean-based blind injection:**

```
Request:  /api/users?id=1 AND 1=1    --> Returns user (condition true)
Request:  /api/users?id=1 AND 1=2    --> Returns nothing (condition false)

The attacker now knows they can inject SQL and extract data one bit at a time:
/api/users?id=1 AND (SELECT LENGTH(password) FROM users WHERE id=1) > 10
```

**Time-based blind injection:**

```
Request:  /api/users?id=1; SELECT CASE WHEN (1=1) THEN pg_sleep(5) ELSE pg_sleep(0) END--
Result:   Response takes 5 seconds --> condition is true

The attacker extracts data by measuring response times.
```

### 3. Second-Order SQL Injection

The malicious input is stored first and executed later in a different query.

```js
// Step 1: Attacker registers with a crafted username
// Username: admin'--
await pool.query(
  `INSERT INTO users (username, email) VALUES ($1, $2)`,
  [username, email]  // This insert is safe -- parameterized
);

// Step 2: Later, a different part of the app uses the stored username unsafely
const user = await pool.query('SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1', [userId]);
const username = user.rows[0].username; // "admin'--"

// VULNERABLE: Using the stored value without parameterization
const logs = await pool.query(
  `SELECT * FROM audit_log WHERE username = '${username}'`
  // Becomes: SELECT * FROM audit_log WHERE username = 'admin'--'
);
```

### 4. UNION-Based SQL Injection

The attacker appends a UNION SELECT to extract data from other tables.

```
Normal:   SELECT name, email FROM users WHERE id = 1
Attack:   SELECT name, email FROM users WHERE id = 1 UNION SELECT username, password FROM admin_users--

Result: The response now contains admin credentials
```

```js
// VULNERABLE
app.get('/api/products', async (req, res) => {
  const { category } = req.query;
  // category = "electronics' UNION SELECT username, password FROM users--"
  const result = await pool.query(
    `SELECT name, price FROM products WHERE category = '${category}'`
  );
  res.json(result.rows);
  // Response contains usernames and passwords!
});
```

## Attack Vectors in Node.js Applications

### Raw Query String Concatenation

This is the most obvious vector:

```js
// VULNERABLE: Every string interpolation in a query is a potential injection point
const query = `SELECT * FROM products
  WHERE name LIKE '%${search}%'
  AND category = '${category}'
  AND price < ${maxPrice}
  ORDER BY ${sortColumn} ${sortDirection}`;
```

Every single variable in that query is an injection point.

### Dynamic Table and Column Names

Parameterized queries cannot protect table or column names:

```js
// VULNERABLE: Parameterization does NOT work for identifiers
const result = await pool.query(
  `SELECT * FROM ${tableName} ORDER BY ${sortColumn}`,
);
// tableName = "users; DROP TABLE users--"

// SECURE: Whitelist allowed values
const ALLOWED_TABLES = ['products', 'categories', 'reviews'];
const ALLOWED_SORT_COLUMNS = ['name', 'price', 'created_at'];

if (!ALLOWED_TABLES.includes(tableName)) {
  return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid table' });
}
if (!ALLOWED_SORT_COLUMNS.includes(sortColumn)) {
  return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid sort column' });
}

const result = await pool.query(
  `SELECT * FROM ${tableName} ORDER BY ${sortColumn}`
);
```

### NoSQL Injection (MongoDB)

SQL injection concepts apply to NoSQL databases too:

```js
// VULNERABLE: MongoDB operator injection
app.post('/api/login', async (req, res) => {
  const { username, password } = req.body;
  // If body is: { "username": {"$gt": ""}, "password": {"$gt": ""} }
  // This matches any user with a non-empty username and password
  const user = await db.collection('users').findOne({
    username: username,
    password: password,
  });
});

// SECURE: Validate types before querying
app.post('/api/login', async (req, res) => {
  const { username, password } = req.body;

  if (typeof username !== 'string' || typeof password !== 'string') {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid input' });
  }

  const user = await db.collection('users').findOne({
    username: username,
    password: password,  // In real code, compare hashed passwords
  });
});
```

## Prevention: Defense in Depth

### Layer 1: Parameterized Queries (Primary Defense)

Parameterized queries (also called prepared statements) separate SQL code from data. The database treats parameters as literal values, never as SQL code.

```
Parameterized Query Flow:

+------------------+     +-----------------+     +------------------+
|  Application     |     |  Database       |     |  Query Plan      |
|                  |     |                 |     |                  |
|  Query Template: |---->|  Parse + Plan   |---->|  Cached plan     |
|  SELECT * FROM   |     |  (no user data) |     |  for template    |
|  users WHERE     |     |                 |     |                  |
|  email = $1      |     +-----------------+     +------------------+
|                  |                                     |
|  Parameter:      |     +-----------------+             |
|  "alice@test.com"|---->|  Bind + Execute |<------------+
|                  |     |  (data only)    |
+------------------+     +-----------------+

The user input NEVER becomes part of the SQL syntax.
Even if input is: "'; DROP TABLE users--"
It is treated as the literal string: '; DROP TABLE users--
```

#### With pg (node-postgres)

```js
const { Pool } = require('pg');
const pool = new Pool();

// Parameterized query with positional parameters ($1, $2, ...)
async function findUser(email) {
  const result = await pool.query(
    'SELECT id, email, name FROM users WHERE email = $1',
    [email]
  );
  return result.rows[0];
}

// Multiple parameters
async function findProducts(category, minPrice, maxPrice) {
  const result = await pool.query(
    `SELECT * FROM products
     WHERE category = $1
     AND price BETWEEN $2 AND $3
     ORDER BY price ASC`,
    [category, minPrice, maxPrice]
  );
  return result.rows;
}

// LIKE queries with parameterization
async function searchUsers(searchTerm) {
  const result = await pool.query(
    'SELECT * FROM users WHERE name ILIKE $1',
    [`%${searchTerm}%`]  // The % wildcards go in the parameter, not the query
  );
  return result.rows;
}

// IN clause with parameterization
async function findUsersByIds(ids) {
  // Generate $1, $2, $3... for the number of IDs
  const placeholders = ids.map((_, i) => `$${i + 1}`).join(', ');
  const result = await pool.query(
    `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id IN (${placeholders})`,
    ids
  );
  return result.rows;
}
```

#### With Knex.js

```js
const knex = require('knex')(config);

// Knex automatically parameterizes
async function findUser(email) {
  return knex('users')
    .where({ email })
    .first();
}

// Complex queries
async function searchProducts(filters) {
  let query = knex('products').select('*');

  if (filters.category) {
    query = query.where('category', filters.category);
  }
  if (filters.minPrice) {
    query = query.where('price', '>=', filters.minPrice);
  }
  if (filters.search) {
    query = query.where('name', 'ilike', `%${filters.search}%`);
  }

  return query;
}

// Raw queries in Knex -- use bindings!
async function customQuery(userId) {
  // SECURE: Using ? placeholders with bindings array
  return knex.raw(
    'SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ? AND active = ?',
    [userId, true]
  );
}
```

#### With Prisma

Prisma parameterizes all queries by default through its query builder:

```js
const { PrismaClient } = require('@prisma/client');
const prisma = new PrismaClient();

// Always safe -- Prisma parameterizes automatically
async function findUser(email) {
  return prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { email } });
}

async function searchProducts(search, category) {
  return prisma.product.findMany({
    where: {
      name: { contains: search, mode: 'insensitive' },
      category: category,
    },
  });
}

// If you must use raw SQL with Prisma, use Prisma.sql or $queryRaw
async function rawSearch(term) {
  // SECURE: Tagged template literal parameterizes automatically
  return prisma.$queryRaw`
    SELECT * FROM users WHERE name ILIKE ${`%${term}%`}
  `;
}

// VULNERABLE: Using $queryRawUnsafe with string interpolation
async function unsafeSearch(term) {
  // NEVER do this:
  return prisma.$queryRawUnsafe(
    `SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = '${term}'`
  );
}
```

### Layer 2: Input Validation

Validation is your second line of defense. Even with parameterized queries, validating input catches malformed data early.

```js
const { z } = require('zod');

const ProductSearchSchema = z.object({
  search: z.string().max(100).optional(),
  category: z.enum(['electronics', 'clothing', 'books', 'food']).optional(),
  minPrice: z.coerce.number().min(0).max(1000000).optional(),
  maxPrice: z.coerce.number().min(0).max(1000000).optional(),
  sortBy: z.enum(['name', 'price', 'created_at']).optional().default('name'),
  order: z.enum(['asc', 'desc']).optional().default('asc'),
  page: z.coerce.number().int().min(1).optional().default(1),
  limit: z.coerce.number().int().min(1).max(100).optional().default(20),
});

app.get('/api/products', async (req, res) => {
  const parsed = ProductSearchSchema.safeParse(req.query);

  if (!parsed.success) {
    return res.status(400).json({ errors: parsed.error.issues });
  }

  const { search, category, minPrice, maxPrice, sortBy, order, page, limit } = parsed.data;
  const offset = (page - 1) * limit;

  // All values are now validated and safe to use
  const result = await pool.query(
    `SELECT * FROM products
     WHERE ($1::text IS NULL OR name ILIKE $1)
     AND ($2::text IS NULL OR category = $2)
     AND ($3::numeric IS NULL OR price >= $3)
     AND ($4::numeric IS NULL OR price <= $4)
     ORDER BY ${sortBy} ${order}
     LIMIT $5 OFFSET $6`,
    [
      search ? `%${search}%` : null,
      category || null,
      minPrice ?? null,
      maxPrice ?? null,
      limit,
      offset,
    ]
  );

  res.json(result.rows);
});
```

### Layer 3: Principle of Least Privilege

```sql
-- Create a restricted database user for the application
CREATE USER app_user WITH PASSWORD 'strong_random_password';

-- Grant only what is needed
GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON ALL TABLES IN SCHEMA public TO app_user;

-- NEVER grant these to the application user:
-- DROP, CREATE, ALTER, GRANT, TRUNCATE
-- The app should never need to modify schema

-- For read-only endpoints, use a read-only user
CREATE USER readonly_user WITH PASSWORD 'another_strong_password';
GRANT SELECT ON ALL TABLES IN SCHEMA public TO readonly_user;
```

### Layer 4: Web Application Firewall (WAF)

A WAF can catch common injection patterns before they reach your application:

```js
// Simple SQLi detection middleware (complement to parameterized queries)
function sqlInjectionDetector(req, res, next) {
  const suspiciousPatterns = [
    /('|\")(\s)*(OR|AND)(\s)*('|\"|\d)/i,
    /UNION(\s)+SELECT/i,
    /;\s*(DROP|DELETE|UPDATE|INSERT)/i,
    /\/\*.*\*\//,             // SQL comments
    /--\s/,                   // SQL line comments
    /xp_cmdshell/i,
  ];

  const inputsToCheck = [
    ...Object.values(req.query),
    ...Object.values(req.params),
  ];

  if (req.body && typeof req.body === 'object') {
    inputsToCheck.push(...Object.values(req.body).filter(v => typeof v === 'string'));
  }

  for (const input of inputsToCheck) {
    if (typeof input !== 'string') continue;
    for (const pattern of suspiciousPatterns) {
      if (pattern.test(input)) {
        console.warn('Potential SQLi detected:', { input, pattern: pattern.source, ip: req.ip });
        return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Invalid input detected' });
      }
    }
  }

  next();
}
```

Note: a WAF or pattern detection is a supplementary defense, not a replacement for parameterized queries. Attackers can bypass pattern matching with encoding tricks, case variations, and other evasion techniques.

## Testing for SQL Injection

```js
// Integration test to verify injection resistance
const request = require('supertest');

describe('SQL Injection Prevention', () => {
  const injectionPayloads = [
    "' OR '1'='1",
    "'; DROP TABLE users;--",
    "' UNION SELECT username, password FROM users--",
    "1; DELETE FROM products",
    "' AND 1=1--",
    "admin'--",
    "1 OR 1=1",
  ];

  test.each(injectionPayloads)(
    'should safely handle payload: %s',
    async (payload) => {
      const res = await request(app)
        .get('/api/products')
        .query({ search: payload });

      // Should return 200 with 0 results or 400 for invalid input
      // Should NEVER return all records or cause a 500
      expect([200, 400]).toContain(res.status);

      if (res.status === 200) {
        // Verify it treated the payload as a literal search string
        expect(res.body.length).toBe(0);
      }
    }
  );

  test('should not expose database errors', async () => {
    const res = await request(app)
      .get('/api/products')
      .query({ search: "' OR pg_sleep(5)--" });

    expect(res.status).not.toBe(500);
    expect(res.text).not.toContain('syntax error');
    expect(res.text).not.toContain('pg_catalog');
  });
});
```

## Summary of Defenses

```
+-----+------------------------------+-------------------------------+
| #   | Defense                      | Protects Against              |
+-----+------------------------------+-------------------------------+
| 1   | Parameterized queries        | All SQL injection types       |
| 2   | ORM (Prisma, Knex)           | Most injection by default     |
| 3   | Input validation (Zod/Joi)   | Malformed data, type coercion |
| 4   | Least privilege DB user      | Limits damage if injected     |
| 5   | WAF / pattern detection      | Common automated attacks      |
| 6   | Whitelist for identifiers    | Table/column name injection   |
| 7   | Error message sanitization   | Information disclosure        |
+-----+------------------------------+-------------------------------+
```

