# Joi: Validation Schemas and Integration Patterns

## What Is Joi?

Joi is one of the most established validation libraries in the Node.js ecosystem. Originally part of the hapi framework, Joi has been the go-to validation solution for Express and other frameworks for over a decade. Unlike Zod, Joi predates TypeScript's dominance and focuses purely on runtime validation with an expressive, chainable API.

## Installing Joi

```bash
npm install joi
```

Joi has zero peer dependencies and works in any Node.js environment. For TypeScript projects, types are included in the package.

## Joi vs Zod: When to Use Which

```
┌──────────────────┬───────────────────┬──────────────────┐
│     Feature      │       Joi         │       Zod        │
├──────────────────┼───────────────────┼──────────────────┤
│ Type inference   │ Limited           │ Excellent        │
│ Bundle size      │ ~150KB            │ ~50KB            │
│ Ecosystem        │ Mature, huge      │ Growing fast     │
│ Error messages   │ Very customizable │ Good defaults    │
│ Async validation │ Built-in          │ parseAsync       │
│ Conditional      │ .when() powerful  │ Requires refine  │
│ Best for         │ JS projects,      │ TS projects,     │
│                  │ complex rules     │ type safety      │
└──────────────────┴───────────────────┴──────────────────┘
```

Use Joi when you are working with a plain JavaScript project, need highly customized error messages, or need powerful conditional validation logic. Use Zod when TypeScript type inference is a priority.

## Basic Schema Definition

```js
import Joi from 'joi';

// Primitive schemas
const nameSchema = Joi.string().min(1).max(100).required();
const ageSchema = Joi.number().integer().min(0).max(150);
const emailSchema = Joi.string().email();
const isActiveSchema = Joi.boolean();

// Validate
const { error, value } = nameSchema.validate('Alice');
console.log(value);  // 'Alice'
console.log(error);  // undefined (no error)

const result = nameSchema.validate(42);
console.log(result.error.details[0].message);
// '"value" must be a string'
```

## Object Schemas

```js
const userSchema = Joi.object({
  name: Joi.string().min(1).max(100).required(),
  email: Joi.string().email().required(),
  age: Joi.number().integer().min(13).max(120).required(),
  role: Joi.string().valid('user', 'admin', 'moderator').default('user'),
  bio: Joi.string().max(500).allow('').optional(),
  tags: Joi.array().items(Joi.string()).max(10).default([]),
});

const input = {
  name: 'Alice',
  email: 'alice@example.com',
  age: 28,
};

const { error, value } = userSchema.validate(input);
// value now has defaults applied: { ...input, role: 'user', tags: [] }
```

## Validation Options

Joi's validation behavior is highly configurable:

```js
const schema = Joi.object({
  name: Joi.string().required(),
  email: Joi.string().email().required(),
});

const input = {
  name: 'Alice',
  email: 'alice@example.com',
  extraField: 'should this be here?',
};

// Default: allows unknown keys
schema.validate(input);  // passes, extraField is in value

// stripUnknown: remove unknown keys silently
schema.validate(input, { stripUnknown: true });
// value = { name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' }

// abortEarly: false -- collect ALL errors, not just the first
schema.validate({ name: '', email: 'bad' }, { abortEarly: false });
// error.details contains both errors

// allowUnknown: false (reject unknown keys)
schema.validate(input, { allowUnknown: false });
// error: '"extraField" is not allowed'
```

## String Validations

```js
const stringSchemas = {
  // Built-in formats
  email: Joi.string().email(),
  uri: Joi.string().uri(),
  uuid: Joi.string().uuid(),
  ip: Joi.string().ip({ version: ['ipv4', 'ipv6'] }),
  isoDate: Joi.string().isoDate(),
  isoDuration: Joi.string().isoDuration(),
  hex: Joi.string().hex(),
  base64: Joi.string().base64(),
  dataUri: Joi.string().dataUri(),

  // Pattern matching
  slug: Joi.string().pattern(/^[a-z0-9]+(?:-[a-z0-9]+)*$/),
  alphanumeric: Joi.string().alphanum(),

  // Transformations
  trimmed: Joi.string().trim(),
  lowercase: Joi.string().lowercase(),
  uppercase: Joi.string().uppercase(),

  // Case-insensitive matching
  status: Joi.string().valid('active', 'inactive').insensitive(),

  // Length constraints
  password: Joi.string().min(8).max(128),
};
```

## Number Validations

```js
const numberSchemas = {
  integer: Joi.number().integer(),
  positive: Joi.number().positive(),
  negative: Joi.number().negative(),
  port: Joi.number().port(),  // 0-65535
  range: Joi.number().min(0).max(100),
  precision: Joi.number().precision(2),  // max 2 decimal places
  multiple: Joi.number().multiple(5),
  unsafe: Joi.number().unsafe(),  // allow values outside safe integer range
};
```

## Conditional Validation with .when()

Joi's conditional validation is one of its strongest features:

```js
const paymentSchema = Joi.object({
  method: Joi.string().valid('credit_card', 'bank_transfer', 'paypal').required(),

  // Conditionally required based on method
  cardNumber: Joi.string().creditCard().when('method', {
    is: 'credit_card',
    then: Joi.required(),
    otherwise: Joi.forbidden(),
  }),

  cardExpiry: Joi.string().pattern(/^(0[1-9]|1[0-2])\/\d{2}$/).when('method', {
    is: 'credit_card',
    then: Joi.required(),
    otherwise: Joi.forbidden(),
  }),

  bankAccount: Joi.string().when('method', {
    is: 'bank_transfer',
    then: Joi.required(),
    otherwise: Joi.forbidden(),
  }),

  paypalEmail: Joi.string().email().when('method', {
    is: 'paypal',
    then: Joi.required(),
    otherwise: Joi.forbidden(),
  }),

  amount: Joi.number().positive().precision(2).required(),
  currency: Joi.string().length(3).uppercase().required(),
});

// Valid credit card payment
paymentSchema.validate({
  method: 'credit_card',
  cardNumber: '4111111111111111',
  cardExpiry: '12/25',
  amount: 99.99,
  currency: 'USD',
});

// Invalid: credit_card method but providing bankAccount
paymentSchema.validate({
  method: 'credit_card',
  bankAccount: '12345',  // Error: "bankAccount" is not allowed
  amount: 99.99,
  currency: 'USD',
});
```

## Cross-Field Validation

```js
const dateRangeSchema = Joi.object({
  startDate: Joi.date().iso().required(),
  endDate: Joi.date().iso().min(Joi.ref('startDate')).required(),
});

// Field references
const accountSchema = Joi.object({
  password: Joi.string().min(8).required(),
  confirmPassword: Joi.string()
    .valid(Joi.ref('password'))
    .required()
    .messages({
      'any.only': 'Passwords do not match',
    }),
}).with('password', 'confirmPassword');

// .with() means if password is present, confirmPassword must be too
// .without() means if A is present, B must not be
// .xor() means exactly one of the fields must be present
// .or() means at least one must be present
// .nand() means not both can be present
```

## Custom Error Messages

Joi provides extensive message customization:

```js
const schema = Joi.object({
  username: Joi.string()
    .alphanum()
    .min(3)
    .max(30)
    .required()
    .messages({
      'string.base': 'Username must be text',
      'string.alphanum': 'Username can only contain letters and numbers',
      'string.min': 'Username must be at least {#limit} characters',
      'string.max': 'Username cannot exceed {#limit} characters',
      'any.required': 'Username is required',
    }),

  email: Joi.string()
    .email()
    .required()
    .messages({
      'string.email': 'Please provide a valid email address',
      'any.required': 'Email is required',
    }),

  age: Joi.number()
    .integer()
    .min(13)
    .max(120)
    .messages({
      'number.base': 'Age must be a number',
      'number.min': 'You must be at least {#limit} years old',
    }),
});
```

## Custom Validators

```js
// Using .custom() for complex validations
const passwordSchema = Joi.string()
  .min(8)
  .custom((value, helpers) => {
    if (!/[A-Z]/.test(value)) {
      return helpers.error('password.uppercase');
    }
    if (!/[0-9]/.test(value)) {
      return helpers.error('password.number');
    }
    if (!/[!@#$%^&*]/.test(value)) {
      return helpers.error('password.special');
    }
    return value;  // return the value if valid
  })
  .messages({
    'password.uppercase': 'Password must contain at least one uppercase letter',
    'password.number': 'Password must contain at least one number',
    'password.special': 'Password must contain at least one special character (!@#$%^&*)',
  });

// Async custom validator (e.g., database lookup)
const uniqueEmailSchema = Joi.string()
  .email()
  .external(async (value) => {
    const exists = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { email: value } });
    if (exists) {
      throw new Error('Email already registered');
    }
    return value;
  });

// Use validateAsync for external validators
const result = await schema.validateAsync(input, { externals: true });
```

## Express.js Integration

```js
import Joi from 'joi';
import express from 'express';

// Validation middleware factory
function validateRequest(schemas) {
  return (req, res, next) => {
    const errors = {};
    const options = {
      abortEarly: false,
      stripUnknown: true,
      errors: { wrap: { label: false } },  // cleaner error messages
    };

    for (const [source, schema] of Object.entries(schemas)) {
      if (!schema) continue;

      const { error, value } = schema.validate(req[source], options);

      if (error) {
        errors[source] = error.details.reduce((acc, detail) => {
          const key = detail.path.join('.');
          if (!acc[key]) acc[key] = [];
          acc[key].push(detail.message);
          return acc;
        }, {});
      } else {
        req[source] = value;  // replace with validated/stripped data
      }
    }

    if (Object.keys(errors).length > 0) {
      return res.status(400).json({
        status: 'error',
        message: 'Validation failed',
        errors,
      });
    }

    next();
  };
}

// Define route schemas
const createUserSchemas = {
  body: Joi.object({
    name: Joi.string().trim().min(1).max(100).required(),
    email: Joi.string().email().lowercase().required(),
    password: Joi.string().min(8).max(128).required(),
    role: Joi.string().valid('user', 'admin').default('user'),
  }),
};

const listUsersSchemas = {
  query: Joi.object({
    page: Joi.number().integer().min(1).default(1),
    limit: Joi.number().integer().min(1).max(100).default(20),
    search: Joi.string().trim().max(200).allow(''),
    role: Joi.string().valid('user', 'admin'),
    sortBy: Joi.string().valid('name', 'email', 'createdAt').default('createdAt'),
    order: Joi.string().valid('asc', 'desc').default('desc'),
  }),
};

const getUserSchemas = {
  params: Joi.object({
    id: Joi.string().uuid().required(),
  }),
};

// Apply to routes
const app = express();
app.use(express.json());

const router = express.Router();

router.post('/users', validateRequest(createUserSchemas), (req, res) => {
  const { name, email, password, role } = req.body;
  res.status(201).json({ message: 'User created', data: { name, email, role } });
});

router.get('/users', validateRequest(listUsersSchemas), (req, res) => {
  const { page, limit, search, role, sortBy, order } = req.query;
  res.json({ page, limit, search, role, sortBy, order });
});

router.get('/users/:id', validateRequest(getUserSchemas), (req, res) => {
  const { id } = req.params;
  res.json({ id });
});

app.use('/api', router);
```

## NestJS Integration with Joi

NestJS has built-in Joi support for configuration validation:

```js
import { Module } from '@nestjs/common';
import { ConfigModule } from '@nestjs/config';
import Joi from 'joi';

@Module({
  imports: [
    ConfigModule.forRoot({
      validationSchema: Joi.object({
        NODE_ENV: Joi.string().valid('development', 'production', 'test').required(),
        PORT: Joi.number().port().default(3000),
        DATABASE_URL: Joi.string().uri().required(),
        JWT_SECRET: Joi.string().min(32).required(),
        REDIS_URL: Joi.string().uri().required(),
        LOG_LEVEL: Joi.string().valid('error', 'warn', 'info', 'debug').default('info'),
      }),
      validationOptions: {
        abortEarly: false,
        allowUnknown: true,
      },
    }),
  ],
})
export class AppModule {}
```

## Alternatives and Extending Joi

```js
// Custom Joi extension for phone numbers
const customJoi = Joi.extend((joi) => ({
  type: 'phone',
  base: joi.string(),
  messages: {
    'phone.format': '{{#label}} must be a valid E.164 phone number',
  },
  validate(value, helpers) {
    if (!/^\+[1-9]\d{1,14}$/.test(value)) {
      return { value, errors: helpers.error('phone.format') };
    }
    return { value };
  },
}));

// Use the extension
const contactSchema = Joi.object({
  name: Joi.string().required(),
  phone: customJoi.phone().required(),
});
```

## Error Handling Patterns

```js
// Centralized error handler that understands Joi errors
function errorHandler(err, req, res, next) {
  if (err.isJoi) {
    const errors = err.details.reduce((acc, detail) => {
      const key = detail.path.join('.');
      if (!acc[key]) acc[key] = [];
      acc[key].push(detail.message);
      return acc;
    }, {});

    return res.status(400).json({
      status: 'error',
      message: 'Validation failed',
      errors,
    });
  }

  // Handle other errors
  res.status(500).json({
    status: 'error',
    message: 'Internal server error',
  });
}

app.use(errorHandler);
```

## Summary

Joi is a battle-tested validation library with exceptional conditional validation through `.when()`, deeply customizable error messages, and a mature ecosystem. While it lacks Zod's TypeScript type inference, its rich API and long track record make it an excellent choice for JavaScript projects and complex validation scenarios where conditional logic and custom messages are paramount.

7.4.3.body:
# File Upload Security and Content Validation

## Why File Uploads Are Dangerous

File uploads are one of the most exploited attack surfaces in web applications. A poorly secured upload endpoint can lead to remote code execution, denial of service, server compromise, and data exfiltration. Unlike text input validation where you check strings and numbers, file uploads require you to validate binary content, enforce size limits, verify MIME types, scan for malware signatures, and store files safely.

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              File Upload Attack Surface               │
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                      │
│  Client ───upload──► Server                          │
│                                                      │
│  Attack Vectors:                                     │
│  1. Executable disguised as image (.php.jpg)         │
│  2. Oversized file causing disk exhaustion           │
│  3. Path traversal in filename (../../etc/passwd)    │
│  4. Polyglot files (valid image + embedded script)   │
│  5. Zip bombs (tiny file, expands to gigabytes)      │
│  6. XML bombs in SVG/DOCX (billion laughs attack)    │
│  7. EXIF data containing scripts or PII             │
│  8. Content-type spoofing                            │
│                                                      │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

## Setting Up Multer for File Uploads

Multer is the standard multipart/form-data middleware for Express:

```bash
npm install multer
npm install --save-dev @types/multer  # TypeScript types
```

```js
import express from 'express';
import multer from 'multer';
import path from 'node:path';
import crypto from 'node:crypto';

const app = express();

// INSECURE: never use the original filename directly
// const upload = multer({ dest: 'uploads/' });

// SECURE: custom storage with sanitized filenames
const storage = multer.diskStorage({
  destination: (req, file, cb) => {
    cb(null, '/var/uploads/tmp');
  },
  filename: (req, file, cb) => {
    // Generate a random filename, preserve extension
    const ext = path.extname(file.originalname).toLowerCase();
    const randomName = crypto.randomBytes(16).toString('hex');
    cb(null, `${randomName}${ext}`);
  },
});

// Configure limits
const upload = multer({
  storage,
  limits: {
    fileSize: 5 * 1024 * 1024,     // 5MB max
    files: 5,                        // max 5 files per request
    fields: 10,                      // max 10 non-file fields
    fieldNameSize: 100,              // max field name length
    fieldSize: 1024,                 // max field value size
  },
  fileFilter: (req, file, cb) => {
    // Whitelist allowed MIME types
    const allowedMimes = [
      'image/jpeg',
      'image/png',
      'image/gif',
      'image/webp',
      'application/pdf',
    ];

    if (allowedMimes.includes(file.mimetype)) {
      cb(null, true);
    } else {
      cb(new Error(`File type ${file.mimetype} is not allowed`));
    }
  },
});
```

## Why MIME Type Checking Is Not Enough

The `file.mimetype` from Multer comes from the `Content-Type` header set by the client. An attacker can trivially set this to `image/jpeg` while uploading a PHP script. You must validate the actual file content.

```
┌────────────────┐     ┌─────────────────┐     ┌──────────────────┐
│  Client sends  │     │  Multer checks  │     │  You must check  │
│  Content-Type  │────►│  file.mimetype  │────►│  actual bytes    │
│  (untrusted!)  │     │  (untrusted!)   │     │  (magic numbers) │
└────────────────┘     └─────────────────┘     └──────────────────┘
```

## Magic Number Validation

Every file format has a signature (magic bytes) at the beginning of the file. Use the `file-type` library to detect the real type:

```bash
npm install file-type
```

```js
import { fileTypeFromBuffer, fileTypeFromFile } from 'file-type';
import fs from 'node:fs/promises';

async function validateFileContent(filePath, allowedTypes) {
  const fileType = await fileTypeFromFile(filePath);

  if (!fileType) {
    throw new Error('Unable to determine file type');
  }

  if (!allowedTypes.includes(fileType.mime)) {
    throw new Error(
      `File content is ${fileType.mime}, expected one of: ${allowedTypes.join(', ')}`
    );
  }

  return fileType;
}

// Usage
const allowedImageTypes = ['image/jpeg', 'image/png', 'image/gif', 'image/webp'];

try {
  const type = await validateFileContent('/var/uploads/tmp/abc123.jpg', allowedImageTypes);
  console.log(`Validated: ${type.mime} (.${type.ext})`);
} catch (err) {
  // Delete the suspicious file
  await fs.unlink('/var/uploads/tmp/abc123.jpg');
  console.error(`Rejected: ${err.message}`);
}
```

## Filename Sanitization

Filenames from clients can contain path traversal attacks, null bytes, and special characters:

```js
import path from 'node:path';
import crypto from 'node:crypto';

function sanitizeFilename(originalName) {
  // Remove path components (prevent ../../etc/passwd)
  const basename = path.basename(originalName);

  // Remove null bytes
  const cleaned = basename.replace(/\0/g, '');

  // Extract and validate extension
  const ext = path.extname(cleaned).toLowerCase();
  const allowedExtensions = ['.jpg', '.jpeg', '.png', '.gif', '.webp', '.pdf'];

  if (!allowedExtensions.includes(ext)) {
    throw new Error(`Extension ${ext} is not allowed`);
  }

  // Generate a safe filename
  const safeName = crypto.randomBytes(16).toString('hex');
  return `${safeName}${ext}`;
}

// Dangerous inputs and their sanitized outputs:
// '../../etc/passwd'           -> Error (no allowed extension)
// 'shell.php.jpg'              -> 'a1b2c3d4e5f6...jpg'
// 'photo.jpg\0.php'            -> 'a1b2c3d4e5f6...php' -> Error
// '../../../tmp/evil.jpg'      -> 'a1b2c3d4e5f6...jpg'
```

## Image-Specific Validation with Sharp

For image uploads, use `sharp` to validate and re-process images, which strips any embedded malicious content:

```bash
npm install sharp
```

```js
import sharp from 'sharp';
import fs from 'node:fs/promises';

async function processAndValidateImage(inputPath, outputPath, options = {}) {
  const {
    maxWidth = 2048,
    maxHeight = 2048,
    maxSizeBytes = 5 * 1024 * 1024,
    quality = 85,
  } = options;

  // Check file size first
  const stats = await fs.stat(inputPath);
  if (stats.size > maxSizeBytes) {
    throw new Error(`File size ${stats.size} exceeds maximum ${maxSizeBytes}`);
  }

  try {
    const metadata = await sharp(inputPath).metadata();

    // Validate dimensions
    if (metadata.width > maxWidth * 4 || metadata.height > maxHeight * 4) {
      throw new Error('Image dimensions are unreasonably large');
    }

    // Re-encode the image (strips EXIF, embedded scripts, etc.)
    await sharp(inputPath)
      .resize(maxWidth, maxHeight, {
        fit: 'inside',
        withoutEnlargement: true,
      })
      .jpeg({ quality, mozjpeg: true })  // or .png(), .webp()
      .toFile(outputPath);

    // Delete the original unprocessed file
    await fs.unlink(inputPath);

    return {
      width: metadata.width,
      height: metadata.height,
      format: metadata.format,
      processedPath: outputPath,
    };
  } catch (err) {
    // If sharp cannot process it, it is not a valid image
    await fs.unlink(inputPath).catch(() => {});
    throw new Error(`Invalid image file: ${err.message}`);
  }
}
```

Re-encoding through sharp is one of the best defenses: if a file is not truly a valid image, sharp will fail to process it. And even if the image contains embedded malicious payloads in metadata or trailing bytes, re-encoding strips them.

## Complete Secure Upload Endpoint

```js
import express from 'express';
import multer from 'multer';
import sharp from 'sharp';
import { fileTypeFromFile } from 'file-type';
import crypto from 'node:crypto';
import path from 'node:path';
import fs from 'node:fs/promises';

const UPLOAD_DIR = '/var/uploads';
const TEMP_DIR = path.join(UPLOAD_DIR, 'tmp');
const FINAL_DIR = path.join(UPLOAD_DIR, 'images');

// Ensure directories exist
await fs.mkdir(TEMP_DIR, { recursive: true });
await fs.mkdir(FINAL_DIR, { recursive: true });

const upload = multer({
  storage: multer.diskStorage({
    destination: TEMP_DIR,
    filename: (req, file, cb) => {
      const name = crypto.randomBytes(16).toString('hex');
      const ext = path.extname(file.originalname).toLowerCase();
      cb(null, `${name}${ext}`);
    },
  }),
  limits: {
    fileSize: 10 * 1024 * 1024,  // 10MB raw upload limit
    files: 1,
  },
  fileFilter: (req, file, cb) => {
    const allowed = ['image/jpeg', 'image/png', 'image/webp', 'image/gif'];
    if (allowed.includes(file.mimetype)) {
      cb(null, true);
    } else {
      cb(new multer.MulterError('LIMIT_UNEXPECTED_FILE', file.fieldname));
    }
  },
});

const app = express();

app.post('/api/upload/avatar', upload.single('avatar'), async (req, res) => {
  if (!req.file) {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'No file uploaded' });
  }

  const tempPath = req.file.path;

  try {
    // Step 1: Validate magic bytes
    const detectedType = await fileTypeFromFile(tempPath);
    const allowedMimes = ['image/jpeg', 'image/png', 'image/webp', 'image/gif'];

    if (!detectedType || !allowedMimes.includes(detectedType.mime)) {
      await fs.unlink(tempPath);
      return res.status(400).json({
        error: 'Invalid file type',
        detail: `Detected: ${detectedType?.mime || 'unknown'}`,
      });
    }

    // Step 2: Process with sharp (validates, resizes, strips metadata)
    const outputName = `${crypto.randomBytes(16).toString('hex')}.jpg`;
    const outputPath = path.join(FINAL_DIR, outputName);

    const metadata = await sharp(tempPath)
      .resize(800, 800, { fit: 'cover' })
      .jpeg({ quality: 85 })
      .toFile(outputPath);

    // Step 3: Clean up temp file
    await fs.unlink(tempPath);

    // Step 4: Return the URL
    res.status(201).json({
      url: `/uploads/images/${outputName}`,
      width: metadata.width,
      height: metadata.height,
      size: metadata.size,
    });
  } catch (err) {
    // Clean up on any error
    await fs.unlink(tempPath).catch(() => {});
    res.status(500).json({ error: 'Upload processing failed' });
  }
});

// Handle Multer errors
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  if (err instanceof multer.MulterError) {
    const messages = {
      LIMIT_FILE_SIZE: 'File is too large (max 10MB)',
      LIMIT_FILE_COUNT: 'Too many files',
      LIMIT_UNEXPECTED_FILE: 'Unexpected file type',
    };
    return res.status(400).json({
      error: messages[err.code] || err.message,
    });
  }
  next(err);
});
```

## Preventing Zip Bombs and Decompression Attacks

If you accept ZIP, GZIP, or other compressed files, validate the decompressed size before extracting:

```js
import { createReadStream } from 'node:fs';
import { createGunzip } from 'node:zlib';
import { pipeline } from 'node:stream/promises';

async function safeDecompress(inputPath, maxDecompressedSize = 100 * 1024 * 1024) {
  let totalSize = 0;

  const sizeChecker = new (await import('node:stream')).Transform({
    transform(chunk, encoding, callback) {
      totalSize += chunk.length;
      if (totalSize > maxDecompressedSize) {
        callback(new Error(
          `Decompressed size exceeds limit of ${maxDecompressedSize} bytes (zip bomb?)`
        ));
        return;
      }
      callback(null, chunk);
    },
  });

  try {
    await pipeline(
      createReadStream(inputPath),
      createGunzip(),
      sizeChecker,
      // ... write stream or further processing
    );
  } catch (err) {
    throw new Error(`Decompression failed: ${err.message}`);
  }
}
```

## SVG Sanitization

SVG files are XML and can contain embedded JavaScript, external references, and other attack vectors:

```js
import { JSDOM } from 'jsdom';
import createDOMPurify from 'dompurify';

function sanitizeSVG(svgContent) {
  const window = new JSDOM('').window;
  const DOMPurify = createDOMPurify(window);

  const clean = DOMPurify.sanitize(svgContent, {
    USE_PROFILES: { svg: true, svgFilters: true },
    FORBID_TAGS: ['script', 'foreignObject', 'use'],
    FORBID_ATTR: ['onload', 'onerror', 'onclick', 'onmouseover', 'xlink:href'],
  });

  return clean;
}
```

## Storing Files Securely

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              Secure File Storage Strategy             │
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                      │
│  DO:                                                 │
│  - Store outside the web root                        │
│  - Use random filenames (no user input)              │
│  - Serve through a controller (access control)       │
│  - Use a CDN or object storage (S3) for production   │
│  - Set Content-Disposition: attachment for downloads  │
│  - Set X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff               │
│                                                      │
│  DON'T:                                              │
│  - Store in public/ or static/ directory             │
│  - Use original filenames from users                 │
│  - Serve uploaded files without Content-Type check   │
│  - Allow directory listing on upload directories     │
│  - Trust the Content-Type header from the client     │
│                                                      │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

```js
// Serve files through a controlled endpoint
app.get('/api/files/:id', authenticate, async (req, res) => {
  const file = await db.file.findUnique({ where: { id: req.params.id } });

  if (!file) return res.status(404).json({ error: 'File not found' });

  // Check access permissions
  if (file.userId !== req.user.id && req.user.role !== 'admin') {
    return res.status(403).json({ error: 'Access denied' });
  }

  // Set security headers
  res.set({
    'Content-Type': file.mimeType,
    'Content-Disposition': `attachment; filename="${file.originalName}"`,
    'X-Content-Type-Options': 'nosniff',
    'Cache-Control': 'private, max-age=3600',
  });

  const stream = fs.createReadStream(file.storagePath);
  stream.pipe(res);
});
```

## Upload to S3 with Validation

In production, use object storage instead of local disk:

```bash
npm install @aws-sdk/client-s3
```

```js
import { S3Client, PutObjectCommand } from '@aws-sdk/client-s3';
import crypto from 'node:crypto';

const s3 = new S3Client({ region: process.env.AWS_REGION });

async function uploadToS3(fileBuffer, originalName, mimeType) {
  const key = `uploads/${crypto.randomBytes(16).toString('hex')}${path.extname(originalName)}`;

  await s3.send(new PutObjectCommand({
    Bucket: process.env.S3_BUCKET,
    Key: key,
    Body: fileBuffer,
    ContentType: mimeType,
    ContentDisposition: 'attachment',
    ServerSideEncryption: 'AES256',
    Metadata: {
      'original-name': encodeURIComponent(originalName),
    },
  }));

  return {
    key,
    url: `https://${process.env.S3_BUCKET}.s3.${process.env.AWS_REGION}.amazonaws.com/${key}`,
  };
}
```

## Summary

File upload security requires defense in depth: limit file sizes at the web server and application level, validate MIME types by reading magic bytes (not trusting headers), sanitize filenames, re-encode images through sharp to strip embedded payloads, protect against zip bombs, store files outside the web root with random names, serve them through controlled endpoints with proper headers, and in production use object storage like S3. Never trust any aspect of a file upload from the client.

